          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">
          How are Palestinians treated in neighboring Arab countries?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          Since 1948, the situation of Palestinian exiles in Arab host countries has changed significantly. Arab states often express political support for the Palestinian cause. Still, they are reluctant to grant full rights or citizenship, fearing it would undermine the right of return or upset domestic demographics.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
         Judicial and political changes, like the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-may-25-tbq-h1-3-casablanca-protocol?source=website" target="_blank">Casablanca Protocol</a>, promised rights for Palestinians, but enforcement has been uneven. However, many rights groups have <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-may-25-tbq-h1-4-criticized-how-neighboring-countries?source=website" target="_blank">criticized how neighboring countries</a> treat Palestinian refugees.</p>
         </mj-text>
         <mj-table font-family="Roboto+Serif" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" padding="10px 18px" style=" width:100%;">
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">â†’</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.6;">
              <strong>In Jordan</strong>, approximately 1.5Mn Palestinians hold citizenship. They are socially and economically integrated, but about 278,000 still live in refugee camps</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">â†’</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
                <strong>In Syria</strong>, Palestinians are treated as stateless but receive rights equal to Syrians in jobs and public services. However, civil and political freedoms are minimal due to a strong state system</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">â†’</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
                <strong>In Lebanon</strong>, conditions are the most challenging. Most Palestinians are stateless, over half live in overcrowded camps, and strict judicial barriers block permission to many jobs. This leads to widespread poverty and exclusion</td>
            </tr>
        </mj-table>
         <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
         Additionally, the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-may-25-tbq-h1-5-palestinian-authority-passport?source=website" target="_blank">Palestinian Authority passport</a> is not helpful for Palestinians to enter most Arab countries without a visa. In addition, the 2Mn Palestinians who can obtain Israeli citizenship are automatically denied entrance to them. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
       Regional politics, such as the expulsion of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-may-25-tbq-h1-6-palestine-liberation-organization?source=website" target="_blank">Palestine Liberation Organization</a> and peace agreements with Israel, have also worsened the situation for Palestinians, especially in Egypt, Kuwait, and Libya.</p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
